# Approach 1: std::unique and std::distance

Using STL functions we can turn this into a one-liner.

```cpp
    static int removeDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {
        return distance(begin(nums), unique(begin(nums), end(nums)));
    }
```

Note that for this problem we don't need to erase the end of the vector, if we wanted that the solution would look something like this:

```cpp
    static int removeDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {
        nums.erase(unique(begin(nums), end(nums)), end(nums));
        return size(nums);
    }
```


**Complexity Analysis**
  * Time Complexity: $$O(n)$$
  * Space Complexity: $$O(1)$$

# Approach 2: hand rolled two pointer solution

The check for an empty vector is strictly speaking not needed for this problem, but I'd add it anyway.

```cpp
    static int removeDuplicates(vector<int>& nums) {
        if (empty(nums)) return 0;

        int w = 1;
        for (int i = 1; i < size(nums); ++i)
            if (nums[i - 1] != nums[i]) nums[w++] = nums[i];
        return w;
    }
```

**Complexity Analysis**
  * Time Complexity: $$O(n)$$
  * Space Complexity: $$O(1)$$

