solutions.content:
Finally after a long time trying to understand so many of the codes here, I myself got to understand one code and get accepted.

Let me break it down to you. It's easy to understand. No messy codes.

**Method 1**: Naive Word Ladder-I continued (TLE) ❌ 
(32 / 35 test cases passed) - Best for interview explanation

```cpp
vector<vector<string>> findLadders(string beginWord, string endWord, vector<string>& wlist){
    vector<vector<string>> res;
    unordered_set<string> wl(begin(wlist), end(wlist));

    queue<vector<string>> paths;
    paths.push({beginWord});

    bool minDepthFound = false;
    while(!paths.empty()){
        int size = paths.size();

		// At each BFS level, we store the erased words to check them again only in same level.
        unordered_set<string> erasedWordsLevel;

		//If the best least level found, break
        if(minDepthFound) break;

        while(size--){
            vector<string> path = paths.front(); paths.pop();
            string lastString = path.back();

			for(int i=0; i<lastString.size(); i++){
                string temp = lastString;
                for(char ch='a'; ch <= 'z'; ch++){
                    temp[i] = ch;
                    if(temp == lastString) continue;

					// The word can be in erasedWords at this level OR in original word list.
					if(wl.count(temp) || erasedWordsLevel.count(temp)){
                        path.push_back(temp);
                        if(temp == endWord){
                            minDepthFound = true;
                            res.push_back(path);
                        }else{
                            paths.push(path);
                            wl.erase(temp);
                            erasedWordsLevel.insert(temp);
                        }
                        path.pop_back();
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return res;
}
```

Lets analyze why TLE in Method 1.
* For each `path` in the `paths` queue, we were taking `path` string array, and appending next possible "**1-letter different word**". So there comes chances that "same words" originate at each of the bfs levels, so we keep finding the next path for the "same word" multiple times.
* Keep in mind this TLE occurs in that node/word, even though its overall `path` is unique.

**Method 2**: BFS, Build Graph and DFS ✅  (It's easy, give it a read)

* Instead of me trying to explain, watch this [video from TechDose](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mIZJIuMpI2M&ab_channel=TECHDOSE). 
* No one can teach you better. You will understand it < 15 mins. 
* Few code changes have to be made to pass the new LC testcases.

**Changes made compared to video are:** 
* We are creating adjacency list in opposite direction. (**beginWord <-- endWord**)
* Similarly, we DFS in the opposite direction from endWord to beginWord.
* That's it.

Reason for taking the reverse direction is basically that will be incomplete-path nodes which is added on each level to the adjacency list. So no point of deep DFS on those nodes. 

Consider it like its difficult to find a node in a big tree from "parent->child", but its easier to find parent from "child->parent". (Thanks [@skate1512](https://leetcode.com/skate1512/))

**BFS + DFS Code**
```cpp
vector<vector<string>> ans;
unordered_map<string, unordered_set<string>> graph;
unordered_map<string, int> visited;

vector<string> path;
void dfs(string& startWord, string& endWord){
    if(startWord == endWord){
        path.push_back(endWord);
        reverse(begin(path), end(path)); // store the answer after reversing
        ans.push_back(path);
        reverse(begin(path), end(path)); // reverse it back cuz backtracking
        path.pop_back();
        return;
    }

    path.push_back(startWord);
    for(string child: graph[startWord])
        dfs(child, endWord);
    path.pop_back();
}

vector<vector<string>> findLadders(string beginWord, string endWord, vector<string>& wordList) {
    unordered_set<string> wl(begin(wordList), end(wordList));
    if(!wl.count(endWord) || wl.empty()) return ans;

	// Visited array stores (string -> bfs level) information
    visited[beginWord] = 0; //level 0

    queue<string> q;
    q.push(beginWord);

    while(!q.empty()){
        string cur = q.front(); q.pop();
        for(int i=0; i < cur.size(); i++){
            string temp = cur;
            for(char ch='a'; ch <= 'z'; ch++){
                temp[i] = ch;
                if(temp == cur) continue;
                if(wl.count(temp)){
					// Unvisited node, simply add to adjacency list
                    if(!visited.count(temp)){
                        visited[temp] = 1 + visited[cur];
                        graph[temp].insert(cur);  // NOTE: beginWord <- endWord is the direction
                        q.push(temp);
                    }
					// direct child nodes check, if both child are at same level, add to adj list, else don't
                    else if(visited[temp] == 1 + visited[cur])
                        graph[temp].insert(cur);  // NOTE: beginWord <- endWord is the direction
                }
            }
        }
    }

	// Reversely DFS from endWord to beginWord
    dfs(endWord, beginWord);
    return ans;
}
```

